# Function to load images and labels
def load_images_from_folders(base_path, img_size=(64, 64)):
    X, y = [], []
    labels = list("ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz")
    label_map = {label: i for i, label in enumerate(labels)}

    for case in ["uppercase", "lowercase"]:
        folder_path = os.path.join(base_path, case)
        for letter in os.listdir(folder_path):  # Loop through A-Z and a-z folders
            letter_path = os.path.join(folder_path, letter)
            if os.path.isdir(letter_path):  # Ensure it's a directory
                for img_file in tqdm(os.listdir(letter_path), desc=f"{letter} letters"):
                    img_path = os.path.join(letter_path, img_file)
                    img = cv2.imread(img_path)
                    img = cv2.resize(img, img_size)
                    X.append(img)
                    y.append(label_map[letter])
        print("\n")

    X = np.array(X, dtype="float32") / 255.0  # Normalize
    y = to_categorical(np.array(y), num_classes=52)  # Convert labels to one-hot
    return X, y

# Define the base LeNet-5 model function with tunable hyperparameters
def build_lenet5_tune(learning_rate=0.001, dropout_rate=0.3, optimizer='adam'):

    model = Sequential([
        # First convolutional layer
        Conv2D(6, kernel_size=(5,5), activation='relu', input_shape=(64,64,3)),  # 6 filters, 5x5 kernel
        BatchNormalization(), # Batch Normalization after Convolution
        MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)), # 2x2 Max Pooling

        # Second convolutional layer
        Conv2D(16, kernel_size=(5,5), activation='relu'), # 16 filters, 5x5 kernel
        BatchNormalization(), # Batch Normalization after Convolution
        MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)), # 2x2 Max Pooling

        # Flatten the feature maps
        Flatten(),

        # Fully connected layers
        Dense(120, activation='relu'), # 120 neurons
        Dropout(dropout_rate), # Dropout for regularization
        Dense(84, activation='relu'), # 84 neurons
        Dropout(dropout_rate), # Dropout for regularization
        Dense(52, activation='softmax') # Output layer with softmax for 52 classes
    ])

    # Define optimizer dynamically
    optimizers = {
        "adam": Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate),
        "sgd": SGD(learning_rate=learning_rate, momentum=0.9),
        "rmsprop": RMSprop(learning_rate=learning_rate)
    }

    # Compile model
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.get(optimizer, Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate)),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# Define tuning functions for VGG16 model
def build_vgg16_tune(learning_rate=0.001, dropout_rate=0.5, optimizer='adam'):

    # Load pre-trained VGG16 model, excluding the top classification layer
    base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(64, 64, 3))

    # Freeze the base model's layers to prevent them from being trained
    base_model.trainable = False  # Important for transfer learning

    # Create the new model by adding custom layers on top of the base model
    model = Sequential([
        base_model,  # The pre-trained VGG16 base
        Flatten(),  # Flatten the output of the convolutional base
        Dense(256, activation='relu'),  # Fully connected layer
        Dropout(dropout_rate),  # Dropout for regularization
        Dense(52, activation='softmax')  # Output layer with softmax for 52 classes
    ])

    # Define optimizer dynamically
    optimizers = {
        "adam": Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate),
        "sgd": SGD(learning_rate=learning_rate, momentum=0.9),
        "rmsprop": RMSprop(learning_rate=learning_rate)
    }

    # Compile model
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.get(optimizer, Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate)),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

def build_lenet5_gru_tune(learning_rate=0.001, dropout_rate=0.5, optimizer='adam'):

    model = Sequential([
        # Convolutional layers (LeNet-5 style) for feature extraction
        Conv2D(6, kernel_size=(5,5), activation='relu', input_shape=(64,64,3)),
        BatchNormalization(),
        MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)),

        Conv2D(16, kernel_size=(5,5), activation='relu'),
        BatchNormalization(),
        MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)),

        Conv2D(32, kernel_size=(3,3), activation='relu'),
        BatchNormalization(),
        MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2)),

        Flatten(),

        # Reshape for GRU input (Let TensorFlow infer time steps dynamically)
        Reshape((-1, 160)),  # Dynamically reshape to (timesteps, features)

        # GRU layers for sequence processing
        GRU(128, return_sequences=True),
        BatchNormalization(),

        GRU(128),
        BatchNormalization(),

        # Fully connected layer
        Dense(84, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal'),
        Dropout(dropout_rate),

        # Output layer with softmax for 52 classes
        Dense(52, activation='softmax')
    ])

    # Define optimizer dynamically
    optimizers = {
        "adam": Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate),
        "sgd": SGD(learning_rate=learning_rate, momentum=0.9),
        "rmsprop": RMSprop(learning_rate=learning_rate)
    }

    # Compile model
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.get(optimizer, Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate)),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

def build_vgg16_gru_tune(learning_rate=0.001, dropout_rate=0.5, optimizer='adam'):

    # Load pre-trained VGG16 model, excluding the top classification layer
    base_model = VGG16(weights='imagenet', include_top=False, input_shape=(64, 64, 3))

    # Freeze the base model's layers for transfer learning
    base_model.trainable = False

    model = Sequential([
        base_model,  # The pre-trained VGG16 base
        Flatten(),  # Flatten the output of the convolutional base

        # Reshape for GRU input (Let TensorFlow infer time steps dynamically)
        Reshape((-1, 512)),  # Dynamically reshape to (timesteps, features)

        # GRU layers for sequence processing
        GRU(128, return_sequences=True),
        BatchNormalization(),

        GRU(128),
        BatchNormalization(),

        Dense(256, activation='relu', kernel_initializer='he_normal'),
        Dropout(dropout_rate),

        Dense(52, activation='softmax')
    ])

    # Define optimizer dynamically
    optimizers = {
        "adam": Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate),
        "sgd": SGD(learning_rate=learning_rate, momentum=0.9),
        "rmsprop": RMSprop(learning_rate=learning_rate)
    }

    # Compile model
    model.compile(optimizer=optimizers.get(optimizer, Adam(learning_rate=learning_rate)),
                  loss='categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# Function to perform tuning
def tune_model(build_fn, model_name, train_X, train_y, val_X, val_y, n_random_trials=5):
    print(f"\n🔍 Tuning {model_name}...")
     
    # Random Search
    best_acc_random = 0
    best_params_random = None
    random_search_space = list(ParameterSampler(param_grid, n_iter=n_random_trials, random_state=42))

    for params in random_search_space:

        print(f"\n🎲 Random Search Testing: {params}\n")
        
        model = build_fn(learning_rate=params['learning_rate'], 
                         dropout_rate=params['dropout_rate'], 
                         optimizer=params['optimizer'])
        
        history = model.fit(train_X, train_y, validation_data=(val_X, val_y),
                            epochs=10, batch_size=params['batch_size'], verbose=1)
        
        val_acc = max(history.history['val_accuracy'])

        # Store best random search parameters
        if val_acc > best_acc_random:
            best_acc_random = val_acc
            best_params_random = params

    print(f"\n✅ Best Random Search Parameters for {model_name}: {best_params_random}\n")

    return best_params_random

# Function to train a model with tuned parameters
def train_model_with_tuned_params(model_name, build_fn, train_X, train_y, val_X, val_y):
    # Extract parameters for the given model
    params = tuned_params[tuned_params['model'] == model_name].iloc[0]
    learning_rate = params['learning_rate']
    dropout_rate = params['dropout_rate']
    optimizer = params['optimizer']
    batch_size = int(params['batch_size'])

    # Build model with tuned parameters
    model = build_fn(learning_rate=learning_rate, dropout_rate=dropout_rate, optimizer=optimizer)

    # Define callbacks
    early_stopping = EarlyStopping(monitor='val_loss', patience=5, restore_best_weights=True)
    model_checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(f"save/tune/{model_name}_best_model.keras", save_best_only=True, monitor='val_accuracy')
    reduce_lr = ReduceLROnPlateau(monitor='val_loss', factor=0.5, patience=3, min_lr=1e-6)

    # Train the model
    history = model.fit(train_X, train_y, validation_data=(val_X, val_y),
                        epochs=50, batch_size=batch_size, verbose=1,
                        callbacks=[early_stopping, model_checkpoint, reduce_lr])

    # Save the training history
    history_df = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
    history_df.to_csv(f"save/tune/{model_name}_training_history.csv", index=False)

    print(f"✅ Model '{model_name}' training completed and history saved.")
    return model, history

In [275]:
def save_all_histories(histories, save_dir="save/tune"):
    all_data = []
    for model_name, history in histories.items():
        # Convert history.history to DataFrame
        history_df = pd.DataFrame(history.history)
        
        # Add model name and epoch columns
        history_df['model'] = model_name
        history_df['epoch'] = history_df.index + 1  # Epochs start at 1

        # Append the DataFrame to the list
        all_data.append(history_df)

        # Save individual history file
        model_history_path = os.path.join(save_dir, f"{model_name}_training_history.csv")
        history_df.to_csv(model_history_path, index=False)
        print(f"✅ Saved training history for model: {model_name}")

    # Concatenate all histories into a single CSV
    final_df = pd.concat(all_data, ignore_index=True)
    csv_filepath = os.path.join(save_dir, "model_performance.csv")
    final_df.to_csv(csv_filepath, index=False)
    print(f"📁 All histories combined and saved to: {csv_filepath}")

# Load all training history CSV files from the save directory
def load_all_training_histories(save_dir="save/tune"):
    history_files = [f for f in os.listdir(save_dir) if f.endswith("_training_history.csv")]
    all_histories = {}
    for file in history_files:
        model_name = file.replace("_training_history.csv", "")
        file_path = os.path.join(save_dir, file)
        history_df = pd.read_csv(file_path)
        all_histories[model_name] = history_df
        print(f"📖 Loaded training history for model: {model_name}")
    return all_histories

def plot_model_performance(history_df, model_name):
    """Plots the training history of a model."""
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
    
    # Plot Accuracy
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(history_df['accuracy'], label='Train Accuracy', marker='o')
    plt.plot(history_df['val_accuracy'], label='Validation Accuracy', marker='o')
    plt.title(f"{model_name} - Accuracy")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.legend()
    
    # Plot Loss
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(history_df['loss'], label='Train Loss', marker='o')
    plt.plot(history_df['val_loss'], label='Validation Loss', marker='o')
    plt.title(f"{model_name} - Loss")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Loss")
    plt.legend()
    
    plt.show()

def plot_metric(history_df, model_name):
    """Plots Training & Validation Loss and Accuracy in one figure."""
    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))

    # Plot Training Loss and Accuracy
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(history_df['loss'], 'r', label="Training Loss")
    plt.plot(history_df['accuracy'], 'b', label="Training Accuracy")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Value")
    plt.title(f"{model_name} - Training Metrics")
    plt.legend()

    # Plot Validation Loss and Accuracy
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(history_df['val_loss'], 'r', label="Validation Loss")
    plt.plot(history_df['val_accuracy'], 'b', label="Validation Accuracy")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.ylabel("Value")
    plt.title(f"{model_name} - Validation Metrics")
    plt.legend()

    plt.show()

def load_all_models(save_dir):
    """Loads all saved models from the specified directory."""
    models = {}
    try:
        for filename in os.listdir(save_dir):
            if filename.endswith(".keras"):  # Updated for .keras models
                model_name = filename[:-6]  # Remove ".keras"
                model_path = os.path.join(save_dir, filename)
                try:
                    model = load_model(model_path)
                    models[model_name] = model
                    print(f"✅ Model '{model_name}' loaded successfully.")
                except Exception as e:
                    print(f"❌ Error loading model '{model_name}': {e}")
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"❌ Error accessing directory '{save_dir}': {e}")
    return models

def evaluate_model(model, model_name, X_test, y_test):
    # Make predictions
    predictions = model.predict(X_test, verbose=1)
    predicted_classes = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)
    true_classes = np.argmax(y_test, axis=1)

    # Calculate metrics
    accuracy = accuracy_score(true_classes, predicted_classes)
    precision = precision_score(true_classes, predicted_classes, average='weighted', zero_division=0)
    recall = recall_score(true_classes, predicted_classes, average='weighted', zero_division=0)
    f1 = f1_score(true_classes, predicted_classes, average='weighted')
    logloss = log_loss(y_test, predictions)
    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_test, predictions, multi_class='ovr')

    # Display results
    print(f"""
    🔹 Model: {model_name}
    🔹 Accuracy: {accuracy:.6f}
    🔹 Precision: {precision:.6f}
    🔹 Recall: {recall:.6f}
    🔹 F1-score: {f1:.6f}
    🔹 Log Loss: {logloss:.6f}
    🔹 ROC-AUC: {roc_auc:.6f}
    """)

    # Return as dictionary
    return {
        "model": model_name,
        "accuracy": accuracy,
        "precision": precision,
        "recall": recall,
        "f1_score": f1,
        "log_loss": logloss,
        "roc_auc": roc_auc
    }

def plot_confusion_matrix(model, X_test, y_test, model_name, labels=None):

    # Predict classes
    y_pred = np.argmax(model.predict(X_test), axis=1)
    y_true = np.argmax(y_test, axis=1)

    # Compute confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)

    # Handle labels if not provided
    if labels is None:
        labels = [str(i) for i in range(y_test.shape[1])]

    # Plot confusion matrix
    plt.figure(figsize=(16, 14))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='d', cmap='Blues', xticklabels=labels, yticklabels=labels)
    plt.xlabel("Predicted", fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel("Actual", fontsize=12)
    plt.title(f"Confusion Matrix - {model_name}", fontsize=14, fontweight='bold')
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(rotation=0)
    plt.show()

        plt.title(f"{model_name}\nActual: {actual}\nPred: {predicted}\nConf: {confidence:.2f}%", color=color, fontsize=10)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def predict_and_display_with_graph(model, model_name, num_images=5):
    """Display predictions with images and top-5 confidence scores."""
    # Ensure valid image count
    num_images = max(1, min(num_images, 10))

    # Randomly select images for prediction
    indices = np.random.choice(len(test_X), num_images, replace=False)
    selected_images = test_X[indices]
    actual_labels = np.argmax(test_y[indices], axis=1)

    # Generate predictions
    predictions = model.predict(selected_images)
    predicted_labels = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)
    confidence_scores = np.max(predictions, axis=1) * 100

    # Set up subplot layout
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_images, 2, figsize=(12, 2 * num_images), gridspec_kw={'width_ratios': [1, 1]})

    for i in range(num_images):
        # Display the selected image
        img_ax = axes[i, 0]
        img_ax.imshow(selected_images[i].reshape(64, 64, 3))
        img_ax.axis("off")

        # Get actual and predicted labels
        actual = labels.get(actual_labels[i], str(actual_labels[i]))
        predicted = labels.get(predicted_labels[i], str(predicted_labels[i]))
        confidence = confidence_scores[i]

        # Color the title based on prediction correctness
        title_color = "green" if actual == predicted else "red"
        img_ax.set_title(f"{model_name}\nActual: {actual}\nPredicted: {predicted}\nConfidence: {confidence:.2f}%", 
                         color=title_color, fontsize=10)

        # Plot top 5 predictions
        bar_ax = axes[i, 1]
        all_confidences = predictions[i] * 100
        top_5_indices = np.argsort(all_confidences)[-5:][::-1]
        top_5_labels = [labels.get(idx, str(idx)) for idx in top_5_indices]
        top_5_scores = [all_confidences[idx] for idx in top_5_indices]

        bar_ax.barh(top_5_labels, top_5_scores, color='skyblue')
        bar_ax.invert_yaxis()
        bar_ax.set_xlim(0, 100)
        bar_ax.set_xlabel("Confidence (%)", fontsize=9)
        bar_ax.set_title("Top 5 Predictions", fontsize=10)
        for j, score in enumerate(top_5_scores):
            bar_ax.text(score + 1, j, f"{score:.2f}%", va='center', fontsize=8)

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def compute_grap(model, model_name):
    """Compute and save GRAP (gradient-based) attributions."""
    try:
        print(f"ℹ️ Running GRAP for {model_name}...")  # Debugging line
        X_sample = tf.Variable(X_test[:1], dtype=tf.float32)  # Ensure TensorFlow variable

        with tf.GradientTape() as tape:
            tape.watch(X_sample)
            preds = model(X_sample)
        
        gradients = tape.gradient(preds, X_sample).numpy()
        
        # Save gradients
        np.save(f"save/gradients/grap_{model_name}.npy", gradients)
        
        # Plot heatmap
        plt.imshow(gradients[0, :, :, 0], cmap="jet")
        plt.colorbar()
        plt.title(f"Gradient Heatmap - {model_name}")
        plt.savefig(f"save/gradients/grap_plot_{model_name}.png")
        plt.close()
        print(f"✅ GRAP analysis saved for '{model_name}'")
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"❌ Error computing GRAP for '{model_name}': {e}")

def display_grap_images(model_names):
    """Display all saved GRAP images."""
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(18, 10))  # Adjust grid size as needed
    axes = axes.ravel()
    
    for i, model_name in enumerate(model_names):
        img_path = f"save/tune/gradients/grap_plot_{model_name}.png"
        if os.path.exists(img_path):
            img = plt.imread(img_path)
            axes[i].imshow(img)
            axes[i].set_title(model_name)
            axes[i].axis("off")
        else:
            print(f"❌ GRAP image not found for {model_name}")
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
